++ in <font color="#00BB00">C:\</font>. I get <font color="#00BB00">C:\itpp-4.3.1</font></li>  <li>Since VS2013 has C99 library support (see <a href="http://blogs.msdn.com/b/vcblog/archive/2013/07/19/c99-library-support-in-visual-studio-2013.aspx" target="_blank" title="">here</a>) in order to avoid warning C4273: inconsistent dll linkage messages copy this updated&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/cmakelists.txt" title="">CMakeLists.txt</a>&nbsp;into <font color="#00BB00">C:\itpp-4.3.1</font><br> </li>  <li>Due to VS2013 C++11 conformance, you must add&nbsp;<font color="#DA4444">#include &lt;algorithm&gt;</font>&nbsp;to the following files:<br> <span></span>- matfunc.h<br> <span></span>- eigen.cpp<br> <span></span>- ls_solve.cpp<br> <span></span>- qr.cpp<br> <span></span>- svd.cpp<br> <span></span>- svec.h</li>  <li>Create the folder <font color="#00BB00">C:\itpp-4.3.1\lib</font> and copy into this folder the following files:&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/blas_win32_mtd.lib" title="">blas_win32_MTd.lib</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/lapack_win32_mtd.lib" title="">lapack_win32_MTd.lib</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/blas_win32_mt.lib" title="">blas_win32_MT.lib</a>,&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/lapack_win32_mt.lib" title="">lapack_win32_MT.lib</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/libfftw3-3_win32.lib" title="">libfftw3-3_win32.lib</a><br> </li>  <li>Copy&nbsp;<a href="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/fftw3.h" title="">fftw3.h</a>&nbsp;in <font color="#00BB00">C:\itpp-4.3.1\itpp</font> </li>  <li>Open a console (Start/Command prompt) and navigate to <font color="#00BB00">C:\itpp-4.3.1</font>. Create the subdirectory build (md build). Navigate to the build subdirectory (cd build) and enter the following command line:<span style="line-height: 1.5; background-color: initial;"><br></span></li> </ul> </div>  <div> <div id="193420209818906091" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"> <pre class="prettyprint"> cmake .. -DFFT_VENDOR=FFTW3 -DFFT_LIBRARIES=C:\itpp-4.3.1\lib\libfftw3-3_win32.lib -DFFT_INCLUDES=C:\itpp-4.3.1\itpp -DLAPACK_LIBRARIES=C:\itpp-4.3.1\lib\lapack_win32_MTd.lib -DBLAS_LIBRARIES=C:\itpp-4.3.1\lib\blas_win32_MTd.lib </pre> </div> </div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"> <ul> <li>At the end of the process, CMake has created a Visual Studio Express 2013 project inside the build&nbsp;<span style="line-height: 1.5; background-color: initial;">subdirectory.</span></li>  <li>Copy the file&nbsp;C:\itpp-4.3.1\build\itpp\itexports.h&nbsp;into&nbsp;C:\itpp-4.3.1\itpp</li>  <li>Open Windows Explorer and navigate to&nbsp;C:\itpp-4.3.1\build. Open&nbsp;itpp.sln&nbsp;(by double-clicking on the icon). Open&nbsp;transform.cpp&nbsp;and modify line 58:<br> Change&nbsp;<font color="#C23B3B">#include &lt;fftw3.h&gt;</font>&nbsp;into&nbsp;<font color="#C23B3B">#include "itpp/fftw3.h"</font><br></li>  <li>Edit the Target Name in the project Properties:</li> </ul> </div>  <div> <div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin" style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a><img src="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/138517_orig.jpg" alt="Picture" style="width:100%;max-width:921px"></a>  <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div> </div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"> <ul> <li>Change the Program Database File name:<br></li> </ul> </div>  <div> <div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin" style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a><img src="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/9607243_orig.jpg" alt="Picture" style="width:100%;max-width:924px"></a>  <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div> </div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"> <ul> <li>Change the Import Library File name:<br></li> </ul> </div>  <div> <div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin" style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a><img src="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/2964086_orig.jpg" alt="Picture" style="width:100%;max-width:920px"></a>  <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div> </div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"> <ul> <li>Launch the building process by (menu Build/Build solution). There shouldn't be any errors and end up with the creation of the following files:<br></li> </ul> </div>  <div> <div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin" style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a><img src="http://nejahi.com/uploads/3/4/9/4/34942308/6170949_orig.jpg" alt="Picture" style="width:100%;max-width:978px"></a>  <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div> </div>  <div> <div id="561871613841355579" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"> <!--wp code prettify-->     <!--//wp code prettify--> </div> </div> ]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Authenticate users on PHP through LDAP server.]]></title><link><![CDATA[http://nejahi.com/personal-blog/authenticate-users-on-php-using-ldap-server]]></link><comments><![CDATA[http://nejahi.com/personal-blog/authenticate-users-on-php-using-ldap-server#comments]]></comments><pubDate>Fri, 17 Jul 2015 08:21:20 GMT</pubDate><category><![CDATA[ldap]]></category><category><![CDATA[php]]></category><guid isPermaLink="false">http://nejahi.com/personal-blog/authenticate-users-on-php-using-ldap-server</guid><description><![CDATA[In one of my projects I came across a situation where I had to authenticate users from an LDAP server. It took me awhile to understand how to work with it so I thought maybe this information might help other people.&nbsp;Depending on the server we might take different approaches to connect to LDAP server and fetch information. Some servers use mutliple Relative Distinguished Name (RDN) as a Distinguished Name (DN) or some will use just one. The rest should be similar for both of these types.In t [...] ]]></description><content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">In one of my projects I came across a situation where I had to authenticate users from an LDAP server. It took me awhile to understand how to work with it so I thought maybe this information might help other people.&nbsp;<br><span style="line-height: 1.5; background-color: initial;">Depending on the server we might take different approaches to connect to LDAP server and fetch information. Some servers use mutliple Relative Distinguished Name (RDN) as a Distinguished Name (DN) or some will use just one. The rest should be similar for both of these types.</span><br>In this <a href="http://php.net/manual/en/book.ldap.php" title="">link</a> there is list of ldap functions built in PHP. In our case we only two function: <strong><a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.ldap-connect.php" title="">ldap_connect</a></strong> and <strong><a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.ldap-bind.php" title="">ldap_bind</a>.</strong><br>The first function make a connection to an LDAP server and the second&nbsp;binds to the LDAP directory with specified user id and password.<br>Now using the following template we can simply authenticate a user but there is a difference which we will talk soon.<br></div><div><div id="509806649159380171" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><pre class="prettyprint">function ldap_med_campus($uname, $password){<br>        $dn = "DOMAIN\\$uname";<br>        $ldappass = "$password"; <br>        ldap_set_option(NULL, LDAP_OPT_DEBUG_LEVEL, 7); <br>        $ldapconn = @ldap_connect("ldap.xxx.yyy.edu",389) or die("Cannot connect to LDAP server!");<br>        ldap_set_option($ldapconn, LDAP_OPT_PROTOCOL_VERSION, 3); <br>        ldap_set_option($ldapconn, LDAP_OPT_REFERRALS, 0); <br>        if($ldapconn) {<br>                $ldapbind = ldap_bind($ldapconn, $dn, $ldappass);<br>                if($ldapbind) {<br>                        return "Success!";<br>                } else {<br>                        return "Invalid Credential!";<br>                }<br>        } else { <br>                return "Connection Failed!";<br>        } <br>        return "Unknown Error!";<br>}</pre></div></div><div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">Now the difference between some servers is the format of DN.<br>As we can see in the example above this code can be used for one of servers I was using which was an Active Directory (AD) and uses only one RDN to identify the users. DN in this case is just simply domain and username in the format of "DOMAIN\\Username". Some other servers might use multiple RDN which might take more information like "common name" or "cn", "DNS domain name" or "dc", "Organizational Unit" or "ou" and etc.&nbsp;<br>An example of this format can be like:<br></div><div><div id="820255061514642035" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><pre class="prettyprint">$dn = "uid=$uname,ou=People,dc=xxx,dc=edu";</pre></div></div><div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">More details about DN and RDN can be found&nbsp;<a href="http://www.zytrax.com/books/ldap/apa/dn-rdn.html" target="_blank" title="">here</a>.</div><div><div id="391108252414943944" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><!--wp code prettify-->    <!--//wp code prettify--></div></div>]]></content:encoded></item></channel></rss>